content.description:
Clip the first bolt of Bone Machine then head straight up the right facing corner past a couple bolts and mixed gear. Step left at the first roof then back right before tackling the next roof. Pull a tough sequence to get established on the thin face. Crimp your way up to a good rest before pulling the last bulge. A few easy moves take you to the top.

Start near the base of the big corner of The Boulevard. Shares the first bolt with Bone Machine.
7 bolts, gear from #.4 to #2

Start up Snakepeel to a comfy ledge. Place some protection in the cracks on Snakepeel then move right and climb the slab between Snakepeel and It's a Way of Life. Cross over It's a Way of Life and climb cracks on the vertical wall. Step left at the top to the rap ring anchor.

Climbs the slab between the distinct cracks of Snakepeel and It's a Way of Life.
single rack to 1"

A long pitch of adventure climbing. The route starts on less than perfect rock which is hard to protect so bolts have been added since the first ascent many years ago with permission from the fa team. After about 10 meters the rock quality improves dramatically and gear abounds.  Following the bolted section continue up toward a overhanging roof/notch.  There is good gear below and at the roof. Make an awkward pull through the roof to a nice stance. Clip a pin then move slightly right and up through some really nice flakes aiming for a right facing corner above and slightly left. Climb the corner to a tree anchor.  If you would like to link this pitch with Astro Boggie and Skywalker, after topping out continue up and left to a ledge where you will find a bolted anchor where you can belay from.



Far left hand side of Joe's Garage immediately left of Telefunken. Do not climb this route with a 60 meter rope. 

Double rack to #1 BD cams. Single #2 to 4. 4 bolts, chain anchor on a tree. Rap the route with a 70 meter rope.

climbs.name: Astro-Boogie
climbs.fa: Greg Hughes and Kate Trecartin, May 2109

content.description:
This is a variation of Astroboy Direct. After clipping the last bolt of Astroboy Direct gain the horizontal ledge and do a foot traverse right to the Bullwhip Days anchor. Exciting moves but well protected. After passing the anchor move up and right to a stellar hand/fist crack that leads to a sloping ledge under a right facing corner. Nothing harder than 5.8 on the variation. Belay on the ledge off a Spruce tree.

Climb any route on L-Shape that will take you to the large belay ledge. Locate the start of Astroboy Direct which is a line of 5 bolts on the wall to the right. 
5 bolts on Astroboy Direct and then a standard rack after that.

Seldom climbed since Astroboy Direct was put up. Start on a ledge with a pine tree, about half way up the second pitch of Waterwalk. Traverse right in a horizontal crack to gain the beautiful vertical crack shared with Astroboy Direct.

Starts from the big ledge with a pine tree about half way up pitch 2 of Waterwalk or the Boulevard.
standard rack

A Cochrane Lane Classic! From the ledge, climb the vertical face past 5 bolts. Traverse right a few feet in a horizontal break to gain the base of a beautiful crack. Follow the crack to a ledge with a bolted anchor.

Start from the large ledge at the top of Waterwalk pitch 1. Can be accessed by climbing any of the routes which end on that ledge
5 bolts. standard rack for the crack

From the big first pitch ledge, climb the thin and technical bolted face following the prominent black streak. When you reach a horizontal crack, step left into the zig-zagging crack which leads into the vertical crack of Astroboy/Astroboy Direct.

Note: After the last bolt/horizontal crack it is also possible to face climb up and right to end on the anchors for Bullwhip Days, but this line is slightly less direct and finishing up the Astroboy crack is much better.

Starts on the large ledge at the top of P1 of Waterwalk or other routes in the area.
Bolts for the technical face. standard rack for the crack

A classic Joe's Garage face climb. Sustained climbing up the imposing wall makes for an intimidating and exposed lead.
Start near the base of the L-Shape corner. Trend up and left for the first few bolts then pull a small roof and continue straight up the face.

12 bolts

climbs.name: Bullwhip days
climbs.fa: FA: M. Leblanc, G. Losier 1996, FFA: D. Caron, A. Dowding June 2012

content.description:
Technical face climbing right of Astroboy Direct. Start at the rap station at the base of Astroboy direct and traverse on a horizontal crack to get to a bolted face split by more horizontal cracks. Bring small cams for the horizontal cracks. Nothing bigger than a 0.75 BD was used on the FFA. Bolted by A. Morgan. Climb Waterwalk or Trundling by Moonlight or Sparky start variation. From the ledge aim for anchor at the base of Astroboy Direct. Your belayer can belay from the other anchor (more comfy) 3 bolts+gear and Bolted anchor.
Look lower in the comments box for the exact gear I used on the FFA.

Climb part of the Boulevard until it is possible to clip a bolt on the face to the right. Make a few moves up to a stance at some stalactite-like features. Follow bolts up the very thin face then join Bullwhip Days at the vertical crack/seam.
From the top, either rap to the ground with a 70m rope or with a 60m rope, rap to the big ledge then a second rap to the ground.

standard rack. bolts at the crux

Climb up easy slabs to a nice juggy flake (there used to be a small tree here). A technical crux trending left will lead you to a crack. Follow this to a right facing corner then easy climbing to the top.
The crux can be protected with a blind nut placement in a horizontal-ish crack if you know where it is. Otherwise solid gear is available at the juggy flake.

An excellent and bold lead.

Standard rack

Right of the arch, climb up the face just right of the alcove to a ledge. From the ledge, follow bolts up the face to top.

4 Bolts and a few mix pieces brings you to a 2 ring anchor.

Climb up to a left facing corner capped by a roof. Navigate around the roof moving right onto the arête. Continue straight up past an overlap and run it out on a slab to the shared anchor with Rock Opera.

Start below the big arching roof
standard rack

Climb up Check Your Prostate but instead of trending right to the bolted anchor under the roof, trend left up a technical slab past a couple bolts to gain a stance below the roof. (Be sure to generously extend any gear below the roof). Reach high to clip a bolt then pull an awesome boulder problem crux sequence to gain the easy slab above.

Start up Check Your Prostate
PG gear on the easier climbing. 3 bolts total protecting the hardest moves. bolted anchor

climbs.name: Gumby Roof
climbs.fa: P. Keleher, G. Porter, M. Fellows 1999

content.description:
An excellent and adventurous climb at the grade!
Climb Rock Opera - Start in a corner or on a very large stump. Make your way up to a vertical crack system. When it ends, clip a bolt and make balancy moves up and left to a bolted anchor.
From the anchor, step right onto a slab then pull the impressive roof at the fixed threaded sling/wire. Easier climbing above will take you to some rap rings at the top of the cliff.

Make sure to keep your rope out of the notch at the lip of the roof, especially if someone will be seconding. Some ropes have been damaged this way.

Look for the fixed sling/wire in the big roof. Start up Rock Opera directly below that part of the roof.
standard rack.

This fantastic linkup follows the prominent arch by climbing above it. It only offers a small amount of independent climbing between existing routes but those links are engaging, and the line is very logical as it generally follows the lip of the arch. The result is a long, stout pitch on some of the best rock Cochrane Lane has to offer.

Start up Catholic Girls and climb it to the vertical cracks after its technical crux. Aim up and left into an undercling and a crack, then make another move left onto Solstice. Follow Solstice until just below its last bolt and move left into the diagonal finger crack right above the lip of the arch (shared with Millennial Ego). When this crack ends, make an exposed step over to some easier cracks (Gumby Roof). Follow easy horizontals to a final step where the arch ends then climb up to rap rings (last few meters of Telefunken).

It is possible to clip the 2 bolts on Solstice but they are not in ideal positions for this route and would need to be extended. It is ideal to climb the route entirely on gear with minimal to no extension necessary.



Starts on Catholic Girls, just right of the base of the prominent arch

At least doubles from BD .2 to .5, single .75 and 1, nuts.

At the far right of the wall start in a low pocket. Make your way up ledges and overhangs passing a bolt on the slab and finishing up a small right facing corner.

Right of Jack in a box. Start in low pocket
Standard rack, one bolt

Climb the low angled left trending crack/flake to a ledge and bolted anchor.
A popular first trad lead.

From the Snakepeel area, walk right and around mini cliff to gain a nice platform.
Standard rack

Climb the right side of an overhanging, triangular dihedral. At the top of the dihedral, step left over the dihedral and climb the cracks up to a tree anchor.

standard rack

Bring your big gear!
Shares the start with Sweepstakes. Climb the crack system in the wall until you reach a set of horizontals. Traverse right to the base of the offwidth. Enjoy the short offwidth. A BD #5 is necessary to protect the offwidth. Something larger could also be used.

Starts on the ledge with a pine tree about halfway up the second pitch of Waterwalk or the Boulevard.
Standard rack to at least BD #5

Start up Think Pure Thoughts. At around half height you will see a bolt protecting a face. Climb straight up to the bolt, move left at the horizontal crack then two more bolts lead to the top.
Crimpy and reachy!

shares the start with Think Pure Thoughts
standard rack. mostly mid size

Climb a short thin hands crack which leads into blobby looking rock. Follow these features past some horizontal cracks, ending at a rap station on a ledge.

History: The route originally traversed right to join Snakepeel at it's crux and followed that route to the top. The new rap station on the ledge makes this route completely independent albeit a little shorter.

Just right of the alcove for Sticky Fingers and left of Snakepeel. 
Standard rack

Climb Rock Opera to where you would clip the bolt but instead, traverse right, clipping a different bolt on the way to the first pitch anchor of Mon Premier French Kiss. Make a few moves up the corner then break right onto the triangular shaped face (b). Turn the corner and make your way up (b) to a diagonal finger crack. Follow the crack up and left with very poor feet directly above the lip of the arch. One final tricky slab (b) takes you to the anchor.

This climb will test your footwork! Really great movement throughout.

Good rope management (lots of long runners) will allow you to do this route in one pitch. Alternatively it wouldn't be a bad idea to climb it in 2 pitches by stopping at the anchor for Mon Premier French Kiss. This would make managing rope drag much easier and wouldn't change the grade. (pitch 1 being 5.8-5.9 and pitch 2 5.12b)

Variation: Climb the first pitch of Mon Premier French Kiss and link into Milennial Ego for an incredible and more sustained pitch!


About in the middle of Joe's Garage. Shares the start with Rock Opera. Start on a large hollow tree stump and climb the crack-riddled slab, trending slightly left to the vertical crack.
Doubles from BD #.3 - #.5. Singles to #3

Climb all the way through the Giant arch/roof of Joe's Garage.
P1: 5.12-, 50ft. Climb easily up the start of the arch. As the angle of the arch kicks back, use some creative, 3D beta to gain the good stance at the 2-bolt anchor.
P2: 5.11, 70ft. Continue up the arch, passing a wide crack section and crossing over Gumby Roof and Dinah Moe Humm and finish at the Telefunken U-47 anchor.

Gear, some wide.

Climb up easy discontinuous cracks to a stance below the first bolt. Finess your way up the thin less-than-vertical face past 2 more bolts before the climbing eases up. Continue on easier climbing to the base of a small left-facing arch. Clip another bolt and make your way up and left, either above or below the arch, to an anchor.

Variation: From the arch (4th bolt), pull up and right onto the ledge and step right to join Sticky Fingers at its upper crux. This was the way the route was originally climbed before the addition of the current anchor.


Left of the Sticky Fingers Alcove

bolts at the crux. standard rack. a 4th bolt was added and can be used for the left or the original finish. Rap rings.

climbs.name: Pizza
climbs.fa: K. Allard, T. Colpitts, J. Graham 1994

content.description:
Between It's a Way of Life and the dihedral of Jack in a Box, look for a vertical crack. Climb this vertical crack past a small roof. At mid height, step right then continue up easing terrain to the top.

Right of It's a Way of Life and left of the dihedral of Jack in a Box
standard rack, bolted anchor

climbs.name: Polaris
climbs.fa: Greg Hughes and Francois Cote, June 2019

content.description:
Splendid movement on great stone. Mostly 5.6 ish climbing with a couple of 10- moves. 

This route is found directly above Astroboy Direct between Kapow and Chiggers. From the Astroboy anchor move up and just right to a thin crack leading to a narrow ledge. Pull up onto the ledge then step up to a roof. From here the path is obvious because of the two bolts protecting run outs. After moving through the crux continue up and slightly left to a tree anchor with blue tat. Belay and rappel from here.
Single rack to 3. Two bolts, tree anchor.

Climb up a slab to gain a crack. Continue up past one bolt to a bolted anchor below the big roof.

start directly below the giant roof 
standard rack. 1 bolt

Climb the Boulevard for about 60'. Step right and clip the first bolt of Bullwhip Days Direct. Move right on jugs to clip the second bolt. Make tricky moves up and right (crux), aiming for a big obvious sidepull. Fun crimpy climbing takes you to the anchor.


This route starts on the Boulevard, clips the first bolt of Bullwhip Days Direct then climbs the face between Bullwhip Days and Bone Machine.
gear up to #2 or 3 for the Boulevard, then fully bolted. Optional .4-.75 in a horizontal near the top. 70m rope. bolted anchor

Start as for It's a Way of Life but move up and right though a small roof then a face with one bolt.
May feel hard for the grade

Starts a few feet right of It's a Way of Life
standard rack, 1 bolt

The best part of this route is it's position. The crux is right off the belay in a right facing corner crack. Layback or jam up to the beginning of the ridge that leads all the way up to the Some Enchanted Evening anchor. Low 5th class after gaining the ridge but oh so fun with great exposure. 

Two starts are possible. Climb Astro-Boggie which ends just below the right facing corner or walk up and around to the top of the routes on Joe's Garage aiming for the far left end above the Bone Machine anchor. Anchor your belayer and place a piece or two on the wall in front of you and then move out and left on jugs to gain the last part of Astro-Boggie. 
Single rack to 3 or 4 inch piece.

At the base of a left leaning ramp, follow a perfect left leaning crack straight up to rap station on top.

single rack

Climb up the arch and pull out of the arch where there is an obvious vertical finger crack on the face above. Continue up the face past a couple bolts.

History: There used to be bolts on the lower face but the hangers were removed due to controversy about the bolts being too close to the corner. The hangers may or may not be there when you read this, but there is good gear in the corner to the right. Either way, the crux is on gear.


start up the giant arch
gear through the roof. 2 bolts on the face above

Climb up into the alcove and skirt around the right side of the roof. Continue up to a bolt. After clipping the bolt, make a few moves straight up before traversing left into a beautiful crack. Follow this crack to a ledge where the crack gets thin. One final crux takes you to the top.



Starts in an alcove with a triangular roof about 15 ft off the ground

Standard rack. 1 bolt

climbs.name: Sweepstakes
climbs.fa: G. Gilchrist, G. Hull, J. Holmes 1991

content.description:
From the Pine Tree Ledge, climb the crack system and plated crimps up the face to the right of the Boulevard corner. The crack thins near the top and the gear runs out, making the last couple moves a bit spicy before you get to a good ledge and tree anchor. 

Starts from the big ledge with a pine tree about half way up pitch 2 of Waterwalk or the Boulevard.
A variety of gear. A BD #4 can be used but is not necessary.

Climb the slabs and roofs to a tricky crux at the 4th bolt pulling over a roof. Clip one more bolt then continue straight up the long face/slab with beautiful features and a couple small runouts. A final overhang up high then a short slab take you to the bolted anchor at the top of the cliff.

A very fun and underrated route. One of the best mixed routes in the province!

Start about 25 ft right of the base of the L-Shape corner. Look for bolts going up through angular roofs.
5 bolts, single rack to about 1". rap rings

Climb up a short face to a ledge just left of the Central Scrutinizer trees. From here follow crack systems and flakes up and left, ending at the same anchor as Catholic Girls. 

Starts to the right of Catholic Girls and left of The Central Scrutinizer.
standard rack

Same start as It Takes Two To Trundle then move out right on the first big ledge. Pull two small overhangs to stand on the slab at the left facing corner, finish up this corner to the anchors.

Finger sized pieces, bolted anchor.
Just pas L-Shape wall, this is the most popular cliff at Cochrane Lane. It offers some of the finest granite routes in New Brunswick.
